Data Description¶

Overview:¶

  • Source: Kaggle, https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/whenamancodes/predict-diabities/

The dataset used is sourced by "whenamancodes" from the National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases. It is curated to aid in the diagnosis of diabetes among a particular demographic group. This dataset focuses on female patients of Pima Indian heritage who are at least 21 years old. This demographic focus arises from a higher prevalence of diabetes observed within this group, making it an important area of study for diabetes diagnosis.

This date includes a range of diagnostic measurements taken from individuals, which serve as a basis for predicting the presence of diabetes.

Collection¶

The data has been selected from a larger database under specific constraints to provide insights into diabetes occurrence in the selected demographic.

Variable description¶

Pregnancies - Number of times pregnant
Glucose - Glucose concentration
BloodPressure - Diastolic blood pressure
SkinThickness - Skin fold thickness
Insulin - insulin levels in the body
BMI - Body mass index
DiabetesPedigreeFunction - Diabetes pedigree function
Age - years alive
Outcome - Class variable (0 or 1)

  • All the variables are of numeric data type

Target Variable¶

Outcome:

  • Indicates whether the patient has diabetes (1) or not (0).
  • The dependent variable used for model prediction.

Considerstions¶

We are including all the variables for the initial exploratory data analysis, certain variables may have more significance in modeling based on their correlations and impact on the outcome. The process involves evaluating each variable's contribution to the predictive model and making informed decisions about which variables to include for optimal performance.

Question we want to explore¶

  • How do age, BMI, and blood pressure interact, both individually and jointly, to influence the likelihood of developing diabetes among female patients of Pima Indian heritage?

Variables Involved¶

  • Response Variable: Outcome
  • Explanatory Variables:
    Age
    BMI (Body Mass Index)
    Blood Pressure

Method and Plan¶

Statistical Model: A logistic regression model will be created that includes not only the primary effects of age, BMI, and blood pressure but also their interaction terms (Age * BMI, Age * Blood Pressure). This model will let us assess how the influence of BMI and blood pressure on diabetes risk varies with age.

Data Analysis: The interaction terms in the logistic regression model will be used to determine their statistical significance. The significance will be evaluated using p-values, which will indicate whether the interactions have a meaningful impact on the likelihood of diabetes beyond the individual effects of each variable.

Focus of the Question¶

Inference: The primary goal here is to infer the nature of the interactions between age and other risk factors. These interactions can reveal whether the effect of risk factors like BMI and blood pressure on diabetes likelihood increases, decreases or remains stable as age varies. Using this we can work on age specific preventive measures and treatments. Of course, we will validate the interactions using Confidence Interval and p-values.

Prediction: While the focus is on inference, the logistic regression model can also help by estimating the probability of diabetes occurrence by combined effects of age, BMI, and blood pressure. This will benefir healthcare professionals in flagging individualized risk profiles.

How the data will help us address the question of interest¶

The data may show us how age, BMI, and blood pressure affect diabetes risk at different ages. By understanding these changes, healthcare professionals can see which factors matter most at certain ages. This can help them create specific lifestyle changes or treatments to prevent or delay diabetes problems in people at high risk. We would also like to use the data to plot the interactions graphically which makes it more easy to find patterns.

Why is this method appropriate?¶

  • Suitability for binary outcomes: Logistic regression is good for predicting a binary outcome, which aligns with our dependent variable, Outcome.
  • Interpretability: We have coefficients that quantify the impact of independent variables and their interactions on the odds of the outcome.
  • Support for interaction terms: Allows us to explore how the relationship between variables changes with age.

Assumptions:¶

  • Linearity: The independent variables and interactions are assumed to have a linear relationship with the log-odds of the outcome.
  • Independence: Each observation in the dataset is assumed to be independent.
  • Multicollinearity: The variables in the model should not be highly correlated.

Potential Limitations:¶

  • Linearity: If the relationship between predictors and the outcome is non-linear, logistic regression might not capture it well.
  • Sensitivity to Missing Data: Logistic regression requires complete data, so observations with NA values will be omitted, reducing sample size and affecting generalizability.

  • We find out that there are no NA data values.
  • Checking for any implicit null values such as having 0: this matter because it is implausuble to have 0 as a value for Glucose, BloodPressure, SkinThickness, Insulin, BMI, DiabetesPedigreeFunction, Age
In [4]:
# Excluding Outcome and Pregnancies, as having 0 pregnancies is fine and Outcome is default 1 or 0
diabetes_data %>%
  select(-Outcome, -Pregnancies) %>%
  summarise(across(everything(), ~ any(. == 0)))

# . is a placeholder and ~ is a lambda funciton
diabetes_data <- diabetes_data %>%
  mutate(across(
    .cols = -c(Pregnancies, Outcome),
    .fns = ~ replace(., . == 0, NA)
  ))

Visualization¶

Histograms¶

Age: Right-skewed distribution, indicating a younger population with fewer older individuals.

  • Relevance to Question: Younger populations may have different lifestyle factors influencing diabetes risk compared to older populations, where biological aging processes play a more significant role.

BMI: Roughly normal distribution but with a slight right skew.

  • Relevance to Question: BMI is a significant risk factor for diabetes. Understanding the distribution of BMI helps in assessing how widespread obesity is within the population and its potential interaction with age.

BloodPressure: Roughly normal but with a clear central peak around the typical blood pressure range.

Implementation of Logistic Regression¶

  • We will clean our dataset by removing rows with missing (NA) values.
  • Split data into training (80%) and testing (20%) sets.
In [12]:
set.seed(369)

diabetes_data_clean <- na.omit(diabetes_data)
train_indices <- sample(seq_len(nrow(diabetes_data_clean)), size = 0.8 * nrow(diabetes_data_clean))
train_data <- diabetes_data_clean[train_indices, ]
test_data <- diabetes_data_clean[-train_indices, ]

# Model GLM with interaction terms
model <- glm(Outcome ~ Age * BMI + Age * BloodPressure, data = train_data, family = binomial)

model_summary <- tidy(model)
model_gof <- glance(model)

# Predict probabilities on the test set
test_data <- test_data %>%
  mutate(predicted_prob = predict(model, newdata = ., type = "response"),
         predicted_class = ifelse(predicted_prob > 0.5, 1, 0))

Interpretation of results¶

Our model achieved an accuracy of 70.89%, showing a decent ability to predict diabetes outcomes. Age and BMI came close to significance (p-values of 0.095 and 0.068), but the interaction terms (Age:BMI and Age:BloodPressure) don't seem to be impactful (p-values > 0.5). The confusion matrix tells us that 48 non-diabetic cases and 8 diabetic cases were correctly identified, though 16 diabetic cases were missed. This suggests that while age and BMI matter, their combined effects might not add much here, and exploring non-linear trends or more predictors could be the next step.
